===Etymology 1===
From {{etyl|ang|en}} {{m|ang|nōn}}, from a Germanic borrowing of classical {{etyl|la|en}} {{m|la|nōna||ninth hour}} (short for {{m|la|nōna}} {{m|la|hōra}}), feminine of {{m|la|nōnus||ninth}}. Cognate with Dutch {{m|nl|noen}}, obsolete German {{m|de|Non}}, Norwegian {{m|no|non}}.

====Noun====
{{en-noun}}

# {{label|en|obsolete}} The [[ninth]] hour of the day counted from [[sunrise]]; around three o'clock in the afternoon.
# [[time of day|Time of day]] when the [[sun]] is in its [[zenith]]; twelve o'clock in the day, [[midday]].
# {{label|en|obsolete}} The corresponding time in the middle of the night; [[midnight]].
#* '''1885''', When night was at its '''noon''' I heard a voice chanting the Koran in sweetest accents — Sir Richard Burton, ''The Book of the Thousand Nights and One Night'', Night 17:
# {{label|en|figurative}} The highest point; culmination.
#* Motley
#*: In the very '''noon''' of that brilliant life which was destined to be so soon, and so fatally, overshadowed.

